description.text:
Designing and building my own CoreXY printer.
I'm only using 3 printed parts this is one of them its designed to fit 20x20mm extrusion and hold it as a y axis. you will want to m5 tap the 20x20mm extrusion

no adjustment, eccentric spacers or messing about is needed for use with the mini gantry wheels, just
4x m5 25mm bolts
4x m5 standard hex nuts
4x m5 washers
4x mini V wheels
8x m5 lock nuts

it is important to use lock nuts! as the inner diameter of the locking part of the nut is the perfect size to not lock up the mini wheels! put one either end of the wheel the locking part towards the wheel! (so the last lock nut is backwards)

Drill out the 4 holes with a 5mm drill bit to make sure the bolts fit through without being held by the plastic, the nuts on the rear are used to hold the bold straight and in place, if you screw the bolt through the plastic (which is very easy) it is very probable that it will be at a slight angle! (you don't want that)

title: 15mm OD x 4mm ID x 1mm Thick Washer

description.text:
After my shocking, literally Earth shattering success with the 15mm Furniture Foot, I decided to extrude the base layer out into, of course, a washer. No crazy Elf Donut intermediate step this time; I just went right for the proverbial throat and made a washer directly. I know, right?

Anyway, the truth is that I really liked how the Furniture Foot performed in the real world when printed from TPU, so I decided that it was time to mass produce some TPU washers. The earlier washer design that I had made for the Robo 3D tensioner screws was great and all, but I thought it would be nice to have something on hand with that #6 (4mm) center hole and a much larger outer diameter of 15mm. So, the dimensions are thus:

15mm OD x 4mm ID x 1mm Thick.

This makes them pretty handy for a large range of uses. In the near future, I think I'll make up a whole washer pack to cover all of the basic needs. Tiny washers, big washers, basically everything from TO-220 heatsink washers to garden hose gasket type washers. Then you nor I ever need to go visit Lowes for a washer ever again, at least until the printer breaks on Tuesday.

Notes:

These come off SO nice in TPU. I'm using the black Hatchbox 1.75mm stuff Here's my basic settings, if you need:

240C Extruder, which is probably overkill but it flows great.
110C Hotbed which is definitely overkill but I'm in a hurrry so no time for trial and error.
My hotbed is 1/8" aluminum plate. I usually use unthinned Pledge Floor Finish (water based acrylic, mostly) as a prep, but I'm using Aquanet Super Hold Unscented right now because of last night's mayhem with PETG. It sticks like MAD, it's a bit excessive.
Flow rate on the extruder is 0.95. 1.5mm retraction at 60mm/sec. Print speed 60mm/sec. Crazy, right? But doesn't seem to be a problem so far, probably because of that 240C extrusion temp.
Oh and a Z offset of 0.7mm, which it seems to like. I also kept my PETG settings of 200% width, 90% height and 20% speed on first layer, because like I said time is really short here and I'm DONE playing games with the printer after so much **** from the PETG. If I see no problems in a print, I'm sure as hell not changing a thing till after Christmas.

Also, perhaps the biggest thing - I'm using an E3D V6 Hotend. This thing is definitely more forgiving than the old Hexagon that that Robo 3D came with, plays better with the exotics. Still have issues here and there but it's easier now to understand what's causing those issues. Yes, it was a wild tiger to install on a Robo 3D. I'm trying to forget all the headache of that day. Damned thing worked its way loose on day four despite all my efforts to do it exactly right. Never screamed obscenities so much in all my life, even counting my first relationship, lol. But, it's still the best I've had. The best hotend, I mean. It really likes TPU. :-)

Hi - this is a TV pole mount that requires only one fixing - a simple cavity fixing metal screw anchor that needs one small hole that can be easily repaired once no longer required - ideal for renting! The fixing is in the ceiling and simply prevents any lateral movement and takes no load. The base takes the load and is designed to be non-slip on carpet. I've designed the base and bottom bracket sepearately so both can be printed flat without support. The only bit you cannot see is the small 8mm bolt head in the bottom bracket that slots into the base. The pole is heavy duty 42mm diameter however could have used something lighter. The TV bracket is a professional audio/visual version for mounting on poles.

The semi-clear flexible tube that guides the PLA filament in my Replicator 2 started popping out of the clips on the back; the tube had many indentations from the two clips on the back of the Makerbot.  On rare occassions, the tube would pop out and cause a failed print when the PLA filament got twisted and jammed.  This simple part slides down from the top and holds the tube snuggly with a lot more surface area.  The lower part of the hole where the tube fits is smaller in diameter so the tube won't push all the way through.  After many hours of printing, it works great!
3 layer, 10% fill does the trick. No raft or supports required.

description.text:

This is a Distilunion style alarm clock for your IPHONE. My wife has an Otterbox Commuter series case so that is what the dimensions are designed around and that is all I am going to guarantee that it works with. The idea is to put your iphone cable into the hole in the back. The hole is sized so that you can slide the usb cable through the hole in the back but not the IPHONE Connector. Then you can slide your IPHONE into the slot and connect it to its charger. Once in the slot, you can use an alarm clock app to set an alarm. This clock was built with the free Snooze Alarm App in mind. https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/snooze-alarm-app/id548321703?ls=1&mt=8 Their is a slot built into the top of the model so that the top flexes and allows you to push the volume buttons to snooze the alarm. There is also a raised mound on the underside of the top that is what actually pushes the volume buttons. I have tested the snooze function and it works. It may be dependent on Sli3er settings however. Support is designed into the model. I have also included the source files.
I used .35mm layer height.  .1mm first layer.  40% infill.  5 solid layers for the top and bottom.  3 perimeters.

Later I will also create a small "snap on" platform for the frame that will carry my small 5.2 GHz FPV transmitter and battery.

description.text:
This project started off with my work on rebuilding my MaxNC-15 CNC Milling Machine. I gutted the old electronics and am installing a Protoneer RPi-CNC and Raspberry Pi to drive it, along with new stepper motors and a bigger power supply. These, I'm mounting to a 1x8 piece of plywood that I am going to bolt to the back of the CNC machine in place of where the original electronics box was located. I needed a way to mount the 36V power supply to the plywood and that began my work with these brackets.

I found this original power supply bracket, but it was about 1mm too narrow to fit my power supply without bowing the clips significantly. Also, I thought to make use of the M4 screw holes on the bottom of the power supply to bolt it to the bracket instead of relying on the friction and springiness of the clips to hold it in place.

So, I wanted to remix it a bit and add 1mm extra distance on the inside and add screw holes that I could bolt the power supply to the bracket. And I also needed the ability to offset those mounting holes to accommodate the terminal cover I had already printed for the power supply. For doing this, I created an OpenSCAD project that imported the original STL and added customizations to easily tweak and add features for things I wanted modified.

Then after printing that, which worked really well, I decided that space-wise on my wood panel, it would be better to rotate the power supply to its side instead. So I added some more customizations to the OpenSCAD code to rotate the base to be one of the clips and move the mounting holes accordingly.

As-is, there's about half-a-dozen different directly renderable configurations in the OpenSCAD code. Simply change the 'RenderType' variable to 0, 1, 2, or 3 (as commented in the code). You can also change the 'RemoveClips' boolean variable to completely remove the clips on the normal base configuration if you want to use only the bottom screw holes to hold it to the power supply (since the clips aren't actually needed in that configuration). And you can change the offset side to be either the inside or the outside by setting the 'OffsetInside' boolean variable, which is useful for the side-mount configuration.

You can easily add/remove extra distance between the clips by the 'ExtraClipDist' variable and you can change the base thickness via the 'ExtraThickness' variable to accommodate counter-boring of the mounting holes. And you can easily set the screw hole diameter and counter bore depth and diameter for both the outside bracket mounting holes and the bottom mounting holes.

I have not, however, added any customizations for the clip height nor for using countersunk screws instead of counter-bored. But, you can easily tweak the OpenSCAD code to add those.

Also, if you are wondering what cover I'm using in the pictures, it's an unmodified print of https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:526278 which fits this power supply very nicely (my make). And the 36V 10A (360W) power supply, I got from stepperonline on eBay.

For printing these, I printed them in ABS at 35% infill (there actually isn't much difference between, 25%, 30%, and 35% on these). I did use supports inside the holes to make them come out a little better, which you can pop out by pushing a screw through them after printing. But, it will print OK without any supports.

Note: I did not enable the online 'Customizer' app for this because that online app doesn't work correctly with importing and modifying an existing STL file in OpenSCAD code, as you can see in the "preview" image of the OpenSCAD file there in the posted file thumbnails. So to customize this, you'll have to download the files and run it on a locally installed copy of OpenSCAD.

UPDATE (13 Nov 2017) : I added V2 of PSU Bracket OpenSCAD that allows for the clip length to be easily altered via new 'ExtraClipLength' variable. See the discussion in the comments tab.
